topic.title: BBC.Christmas.77.with.the.Sex.Pistols.720p.HDTV.x264.AAC.MVGroup.org.mkv
topic.body:
"Christmas 77 with the Sex Pistols", also known as "Never Mind the Baubles", broadcast BBC4, 2013.

Remember when outrageous, transgressive, offensive punk rockers The Sex Pistols played a children's party? No???

Britain, Christmas 1977. The Winter of Discontent, IMF bailouts, strikes, brown flares, Leo Sayer, glam rock and disco. And amid all this, bubbling up from the underground, punk rock: pilloried, slandered, despised. Clearly the tool of Satan that would lead to the fall of civilisation. The Sex Pistols' tour consisted of wandering around the North of England on a bus, as town after town banned their concerts, hotels refused to let them stay, and even roadside restaurants denied them a meal.

And then finally, an invitation to play a benefit for the families of striking firemen, so their kids could have a good meal and a present that year. Johnny Rotten screaming "God Save the Queen!" at cheery seven-year-olds bopping away in their free T-shirts proclaiming "Never Mind the Bollocks". Free skateboards! Sid Vicious smiling!

And three weeks later it was all over, as the Pistols broke up on their failed tour of the US.

This is the story of their last ever concert in England, captured on tape by Julien Temple, the filmmaker behind the punk classic "The Great Rock and Roll Swindle". His mostly-never-seen-before video footage is combined here with archive film from the time and modern-day interviews with all three of the surviving Pistols and fans who were there that fateful evening.

+ https://www.sexpistolsofficial.com/christmas-with-the-sex-pistols/
+ https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/dec/23/sex-pistols-anarachy-film-huddersfield-never-mind-baubles

topic.body:
* Total size: 1.42GB

The Royal Institution Christmas Lectures are, well, an institution. Started by Michael Faraday in 1825, each Christmas scientists explain big scientific concepts in an informative and entertaining way that's easy for all to grasp, young and old.


This year's series of 3 lectures is titled "Who am I?" Professor Alice Roberts (biological anthropologist) and Professor Aoife McLysaght(geneticist) take viewers on an immersive voyage through our evolutionary past and ask challenging questions about what our future holds.


**1 of 3: Where Do I Come From?**
Roberts meets our ancient ancestral family, from armadillos to sharks, and discovers our true place in the tree of life. With 4D scanning, giant origami and a ukulele, they will explore evolution like never before.
